WEBVTT

00:00:00.200 --> 00:00:04.487
This walkthrough builds an interactive
account-risk assistant with Oracle AI

00:00:04.487 --> 00:00:10.679
Database, AG-UI, A2UI, the Oracle Database
MCP Java Toolkit, and an optional MCP App.

00:00:10.679 --> 00:00:15.443
The result is a governed workflow, not
just a text answer.

00:00:15.843 --> 00:00:20.075
The browser receives AG-UI events and A2UI
interface updates.

00:00:20.075 --> 00:00:24.308
The Java service owns orchestration,
validation, and human approval.

00:00:24.308 --> 00:00:29.599
The MCP Toolkit exposes governed database
capabilities that multiple agents and

00:00:29.599 --> 00:00:31.715
MCP-compatible clients can reuse.

00:00:32.115 --> 00:00:37.246
The default application now launches the
pinned Oracle Database MCP Java Toolkit

00:00:37.246 --> 00:00:39.579
over standard input and output.

00:00:39.579 --> 00:00:44.710
It initializes the MCP session, verifies
the server identity, and fails closed

00:00:44.710 --> 00:00:47.509
unless exactly five account-risk tools are
available.

00:00:47.909 --> 00:00:51.727
The Toolkit configuration enables
purpose-built reads, action identifier

00:00:51.727 --> 00:00:55.545
reservation, the procedure-backed write,
and a verification count.

00:00:55.545 --> 00:00:58.273
All database values are binds.

00:00:58.273 --> 00:01:03.181
Broad query, write, table, and
administration tools are not enabled.

00:01:03.581 --> 00:01:08.490
Oracle AI Database stores the accounts,
risk evidence, and audited follow-up

00:01:08.490 --> 00:01:08.981
actions.

00:01:08.981 --> 00:01:14.871
The approved MCP tool calls an input-only
procedure that validates inputs, locks the

00:01:14.871 --> 00:01:19.288
selected account, inserts one action, and
updates its status atomically.

00:01:19.688 --> 00:01:25.071
AG-UI streams standard run, text,
tool-call, state, and error events from

00:01:25.071 --> 00:01:28.300
the Java service to the browser.

00:01:28.300 --> 00:01:33.682
A2UI envelopes travel inside an AG-UI
custom event named a2ui.message, keeping

00:01:33.682 --> 00:01:35.835
transport and interface responsibilities
distinct.

00:01:36.235 --> 00:01:42.227
The browser accepts only A2UI version zero
point nine point one, the expected surface

00:01:42.227 --> 00:01:44.992
and catalog, and a small component
allowlist.

00:01:44.992 --> 00:01:50.984
Generated values enter the page as text,
so the agent cannot inject executable HTML

00:01:50.984 --> 00:01:51.906
or JavaScript.

00:01:52.306 --> 00:01:56.880
For compatible conversational hosts, the
optional MCP App registers a sandboxed

00:01:56.880 --> 00:01:57.795
dashboard resource.

00:01:57.795 --> 00:02:03.742
Sandboxing is part of the MCP Apps host
model, not merely a demo choice.

00:02:03.742 --> 00:02:08.774
Structured account data crosses the host
bridge, while database credentials do not.

00:02:09.174 --> 00:02:14.158
In the application, the user sets a risk
threshold and row limit.

00:02:14.158 --> 00:02:19.596
The AG-UI event rail shows run and MCP
tool activity, while A2UI renders

00:02:19.596 --> 00:02:22.768
selectable account cards, risk
explanations, and approval controls.

00:02:23.168 --> 00:02:28.669
Approval is bound to the actor, returned
account set, and a short-lived single-use

00:02:28.669 --> 00:02:29.128
identifier.

00:02:29.128 --> 00:02:34.170
Approve invokes the bounded MCP tools and
displays the committed action identifier.

00:02:34.170 --> 00:02:37.838
Cancel consumes the approval without
creating a database action.

00:02:38.238 --> 00:02:42.785
Each component keeps one clear
responsibility: AG-UI streams, A2UI

00:02:42.785 --> 00:02:48.469
describes trusted controls, MCP Apps add
rich sandboxed experiences, the MCP

00:02:48.469 --> 00:02:53.016
Toolkit exposes reusable governed
capabilities, and Oracle AI Database

00:02:53.016 --> 00:02:55.289
governs data and transactions.

